data.content:
Here's the xUnit equivalent:

| NUnit | xUnit |
|---|---|
| `[OneTimeSetUp/TearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>` |
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[Test]` | `[Fact]` |

```csharp
// Shared fixture for one-time setup/teardown
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    // Constructor replaces [SetUp]
    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    // IDisposable replaces [TearDown]
    public void Dispose()
    {
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once per class, disposing it after all tests complete. The fixture is injected via the constructor.
- **Constructor/Dispose** — xUnit creates a **new class instance per test**, so constructor = per-test setup and `Dispose()` = per-test teardown.
- **Assertions** — `Assert.That(x, Is.Not.Null)` → `Assert.NotNull(x)`; note `Assert.Equal` takes `(expected, actual)`.

If you need to share the fixture across **multiple test classes**, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
